column25: P B & S CHEMICAL CO INC
column168: A FRA INSPECTOR TOURING THE CSX YARDS IN COLUMBUS, OH DETECTED A SMALL CAUSTIC SODA LEAK FROM THE PACKING AREA OF A TWO-INCH BALL VALVE. THIS LEAK WAS REPORTED TO CHEMTREC. CHEMTREC CALLED P.B. & S. CHEMICAL COMPANY, INC. IN HENDERSON, KY. MR. HAROLD SASSE, EX. VICE PRESIDENT, REPORTED ABOVE INFORMATION TO WRITER. A.R. MORRIS AND KEVIN SHAFFER LEFT NITRO, WV, BY MOTOR VEHICLE TO INSPECT AND TAKE NECESSARY ACTION TO TURN DIRECTED ANOTHER CSX EMPLOYEE TO ACCOMPANY A.R. MORRIS AND KEVIN SHAFFER TO RAILCAR UTLX630019. THE TWO-INCH EXTERNAL VALVE ON BOTTOM OF CAR APPEARED TO BE "DAMP" FROM CAUSTIC SODA. THERE WAS NO DRIPPING DETECTED WHILE IT WAS OBSERVED FOR A FEW MINUTES PRIOR TO TAKING ACTION. THERE WAS EVIDENT (PUDDLE,ETC.) OF ANY DRIPPING ON TO GROUND BELOW VALVE. THE VALVE HANDLE WAS REMOVED TO GAIN ACCESS TO THE PACKING NUT. THE PB&S EMPLOYEES THEN TIGHTENED THE PACKING NUT ABOUT A QUARTER OF A TURN. THE VALVE PACKING NUT WILL BE CHECKED FOR TIGHTNESS ON ALL RAILCARS LOADED AT NITRO, WV.

column168: ALASKA WEST EXPRESS DRIVER WAS TRAVELING NORTH BOUND TO PREDHOE BAY ALASKA, LOADED WITH 8510 GALLONS OF JET-A50. THE WEATHER CONDITIONS TURNED INTO A BLOWING BLIZZARD CREATING WHITE-OUT CONDITION. ON COMING SOUTH BOUND TRAFFIC WAS KICKING UP ADDITIONAL SNOW. VISIBILITY WAS VERY POOR AT BEST. THE DRIVER SLOWED TO A CRAWL, TRYING TO MAINTAIN VISUAL CONTACT WITH THE SHOULDER ON THE ROAD. THE ROAD WAS NOT PLOWED WHICH WAS ALSO CREATING DRIFTING CONDITIONS. THE DRIVER GOT THE RIGHT FRONT TIRES CAUGHT IN THE DRIFTING SNOW/SHOULDER OF THE ROAD. THIS CAUSE HIM TO GER SUCKED DOWN INTO THE DITCH ALONG THE ROAD. THE STEEP EMBANKMENT CAUSE THE TRACTOR/TRAILER UNIT TO GENTLY ROLL ONTO IT'S SIDE.THERE WAS NO MAJOR DAMAGES AT ALL TO THE TRAILER. EVERY MINUTE SEEPAGE WAS AROUND THE FRONT AND REAR DOME LIDS, 100% OF THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED UTILIZING THE SPILL KITS PROVIDED ON EACH ALASKA WEST TRUCK. ALASKA WAS PERSONNEL SHORTLY ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AND PUMP THE PRODUCT INTO AN EMPTY TANKER. NO INJURIES OCCURRED. ANY PRODUCT THAT DID SEEP FROM AROUND THE DOMES LIDS WAS CONTAINED AND NEVER REACHED THE GROUND.

column168: ON 11-6-92, AT APPROXIMATELY 1200 HOURS GREAT WESTERN CHEMICAL EMPLOYEES DAVID HINKEBEIN AND BRIAN HARDMAN WERE ATTEMPTING TO UNLOAD HYDROCHLORIC ACID FROM RAILCAR INTO A TANK TRUCK. THE OPERATION OF UNLOADING WAS COMPLETED AND THEY WERE IN THE PROCESS OF PREPARING TO BLOW AIR THROUGH THE TRANSFER HOSE TO EMPTY IT OUT WHEN THE WEIGHT OF THE HOSE SHIFTED, CAUSING THE PVC FITTING TO BREAK THAT CONNECTED THE RAILCAR TO THE HOSE. THE INCIDENT TOOK PLACE AT GREAT WESTERN'S TEMPORARY FACILITY LOCATED 506 N. 500 W., SALT LAKE CITY, UT 84103. THE RELEASE CONSISTED OF 750 GALLONS OF 22 DEGREES BE HYDROCHLORIC ACID. THE OPERATORS INVOLVED IN THE INCIDENT WERE WEARING FULL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT INCLUDING RESPIRATORS. WHEN THE INCIDENT OCCURRED ACTION WAS TAKEN TO ABATE THE RELEASE AND AT ABOUT 1202 HOURS 911 WAS CALLED. WHILE WAITING FOR THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE ORGANIZATIONS TO ARRIVE, GREAT WESTERN EMPLOYEES USED SODA ASH TO BUILD A DIKE TO LIMIT ENVIRONMENTAL EXPOSURE. ADDITIONAL SODA ASH WAS USED BY GREAT WESTERN EMPLOYEES TO NEUTRALIZE THE RELEASED HYDROCHLORIC ACID. AFTER NEUTRALIZATION WAS COMPLETE THE COMBINED MIXTURE OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID AND SODA ASH WAS REMOVED AND PLACED IN LINED DOT 17H DRUMS. THIS MATERIAL WILL BE DISPOSED OF ACCORDING TO UTAH STATE REGULATIONS. ONE EMPLOYEE WAS TAKEN TO THE SALT LAKE INDUSTRIAL CLINIC FOR OBSERVATION AND RELEASED ONE HOUR LATER. BECAUSE OF LOCALIZED CONTAINMENT WITH SODA ASH, POTENTIAL HAZARDS TO HUMAN HEALTH AND THE ENVIRONMENT WERE MINIMIZED.

ONE OF OUR DRIVER/SALESMEN TRAINEES WAS LOADING A PALLET BEHIND A 55 GALLON DRUM WHEN HE ACCIDENTLY BUMPED AND PUNCTUATED THE DRUM OF FLAMMABLE LIQUID. THE EMPLOYEE CALLED TO ME TO COME OVER TO THE TRAILER. I SAW A SMALL HOLE ON THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM. I TIPPED THE DRUM UP AND ASKED THE EMPLOYEE TO QUICKLY GET A PALLET NEARBY. I LAID THE DRUM ON ITS SIDE WITH THE HOLE UP. A DOCKWORKER SAW THIS HAPPENING AND ALREADY GOT SOME ABSORBANT AND MADE A DAM AT THE TRAILER DOOR. I QUICKLY SPREAD SOME MORE ABSORBANT ON THE TRAILER FLOOR SO THE SPILL WAS KEPT IN THE TRAILER. THIS HAPPENED VERY QUICKLY AND THE TOTAL TIME SPENT WAS APPROX. 30 SECONDS.     I PLAN ON A MEETING WITH THIS EMPLOYEE 11-20-92 TO EXPLAIN THE SERIOUSNESS OF WHAT HAPPENED AND STEPS THAT COULD BE TAKEN TO ENSURE THIS DOES NOT HAPPEN AGAIN. IT APPEARS THAT THE TIP OF THE FORK WAS STICKING OUT PAST THE PALLET APPROX. 1" WHICH PUNCTUATED THE DRUM.

column168: THE VAN TRUCK WAS LOADED WITH "LAB PACKED" DRUMS AT THE POINT REYES HOUSEHOLD WASTE COLLECTION EVENT. THE DRUM INVOLVED IN THIS INCIDENT CONTAINED THREE 5 GALLON BOTTLES OF WASTE ACID (ACETIC ANHYDRIDE), LAB PACKED WITH VERMICULITE AND COVERED WITH A SEALED DRUM LID. THE LOAD OF 119 DRUMS WAS TRANSPORTED TO APPROPRIATE TECHNOLOGIES II, IN CHULA VISTA, CA., WHERE THE DRUMS WERE TO BE UNLOADED. THE DRUM IN QUESTION WAS DROPPED WITHIN THE TRUCK AND IT STRUCK THE FLOOR OF THE TRUCK BED. THE IMPACT CAUSED THE INNER TWO BOTTLES TO BREAK, RELEASING THEIR CONTENTS AND CAUSING A REACTION WHICH PRODUCED ENOUGH PRESSURE TO POP THE LID OFF THE OUTER DRUM. THE ACETIC ANHYDRIDE VAPORIZED. THE PERSONNEL AT THE UNLOADING SITE RESPONDED TO CONTAIN THE MATERIAL. DURING THIS EVENT, TWO EMPLOUEES WERE TAKEN TO A MEDICAL FACILITY FOR OBSERVATION AND THEN RELEASED TO RETURN TO WORK. SINCE APPROPRIATE TECHNOLOGIES IS A TREATMENT, STORAGE AND DISPOSAL FACILITY, THEY WERE WELL PREPARED TO CLEAN-UP AND CONTAIN THE MATERIAl. THE LAB PACKING PROCEDURES ARE BEING REVIEWED SO AS TO ENSURE THAT SIMILAR EVENTS DO NOT OCCUR IN THE FUTURE.

WHILE UNLOADING FREIGHT AT OUR TERMINAL, OUR FORKLIFT OPERATOR PUNCTURED A DRUM THAT WAS IN FRONT OF A PALLET HE WAS MOVING. THE PUNCTURED DRUM AND ALL THE SPILLED ISOPROPANOL WAS PLACED IN AN 85 GALLON RECOVERY DRUM AND WAS SHIPPED BACK TO THE SHIPPER, NALCO CHEMICAL CO., 7701 HWY 90, SUGARLAND, TX.

OUR DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO HOOK UP TO THE CONSIGNEE'S PRODUCT LINE AND PUMP OFF THE PRODUCT (PETROLEUM NAPHTHA). THE CONSIGNEE HAS A GATE VALVE AT THE UNLOADING PIPE. THE CONSIGNEES UNLOADING PIPE GOES THROUGH A BLOCK WALL TO AN ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK. THE PRODUCT WAS UNLOADED AND OUR CARGO TANK, HOSES AND PUMP WENT EMPTY. THE CONSIGNEES PERSONNEL CLOSED THE GATE VALVE AFTER WE HAD COMPLETED OUR DELIVERY. WE DISCONNECTED OUR HOSE AT THE CARGO TANK MOMENTS LATER THE PRODUCT STARTED TO BACK FLOW CAUSING A SPILL. THE CONSIGNEE STATED THAT IN ADDITION TO THE GATE VALVE THEY HAD A CHECK VALVE INSIDE OF THE BUILDING ON THIS PRODUCT PIPE AND STORAGE TANK AND MAYBE IT HAD MALFUNCTIONED. THE CONSIGNEE ABSORBED THE PRODUCT WITH OIL DRI AND PUR INTO CONTAINERS.

column168: THE DRUM WAS PUNCTURED AT THE BASE WHEN A DOCK WORKER LIFTED A DOCK PLATE AND STRUCK THE DRUM. THE DOCK WORKER THEN PUSHED THE DRUM OVER ON ITS SIDE TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE WE THEN CONTACTED THE NUMBER ON THE FREIGHT BILL. IN ADDITION, SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED FOR THE PROPER CLEANUP PROCEDURE. WE WERE INFORMED THAT THE ACID NEEDED TO BE NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH AND THEN RINSED WITH WATER. THIS PROCEDURE WAS FOLLOWED AND THE WATER WAS ALLOWED  TO EVAPORATE. TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING IN THE FUTURE, ALL EMPLOYEES WILL MAKE SURE ALL FREIGHT IS CLEAR BEFORE RAISING THE DOCK PLATE.

OUR DRIVER WAS IN THE PROCESS OF TRANSFERRING HIS CARGO TO STORAGE WHEN HIS UNLOADING HOSE DISCONNECTED. HE SHUT DOWN, RECONNECTED HIS HOSE AND COMPLETED HIS UNLOADING WITHOUT FURTHER DIFFICULTY. A CONTRACTOR WAS ENGAGED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL AREA.

OUR DRIVER STARTED TO PUMP THE MATERIAL TO STORAGE AT HIS DESTINATION AND THE PACKING ON HIS PUMP STARTED TO LEAK. HE PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE PUMP TO CONTAIN THE MATERIAL. DURING THE DELIVERY PROCESS HIS PUMP STARTED TO LEAK BADLY AND SOME OF THE MATERIAL OVERFLOWED THE BUCKET INTO A CONTAINMENT AREA. OUR DRIVER AT THIS JUNCTURE SHUT DOWN REPAIRED THE PACKING IN HIS PUMP AND THEN COMPLETED HIS DELIVERY WITHOUT FURTHER DIFFICULTY.

LOWE, THE MGR OF THE GAS STATION AT THAT TIME OPENED THE CAP ON THE ALREADY FULL MID GRADE TANK CAUSING THE GAS TO SPILL ONTO THE GROUND. THE DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY LIFTED TO THE UPRIGHT POSITION, THE MATERIAL WAS QUICKLY CLEANED UP AND FULLY RECOVERED USING ABSORBENT MATERIAL, AND THE LID AND RING ASSEMBLY WAS INSPECTED TO DETERMINE THE EXTENT OF DAMAGE.  THE INSPECITON RESULTED IN A TIGHTENING OF THE BOLT AND NUT ON THE RING AND WAS THEN CONSIDERED TO BE TRANSPORT WORTHY WITHOUT ANY FURTHER LEAKAGE OCCURING.

AT A TOLL BOOTH ON I95 IN THE BRONX, NY, THE DRIVER WHILE AT THE GATE NOTICED A LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE DECK OF THE TRAILER AND NOTIIED THE DRIVER.  THE DRIVER MOVED THE TRUCK TO THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD AND THE ATTENDANT NOTIFIED THE NY STATE POLICE, WEST CHESTER COUNTY FIRE DEPT., WESTCHESTER COUNTY EMERGENCY RESPONSE,A ND THE COUNTY ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEER.  THE EMR TEAM RESPONDED TO THE SCENE, PLACED THE LEAKING DRUM IN AN OVERPACK CONTINER, AND THE SPILLED HCL WAS CAUSED BY A HOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM WHICH WAS THE RESULT OF ABRASION BETWEEN A WELDED PATCH OF STEEL ON THE DECK AND THE STEEL DRUM. IN THE FUTURE ALL DRUMMED MATERIAL WILL BE PLACED ON WOODEN PALLETS TO AVOID A RECURRENCE.

column168: ON TUESDAY, NOVEMBER 10, 1992, NORTHEAST ENVIROMENTAL SERVICES, INC. (NES) WAS PERFORMING SEVERAL DRUM PICKUPS FOR SHIPMENT BACK TO OUR TSD FACILITY IN CANASTOTA, NEW YORK, UTILIZING OUR 22 FOOT STRAIGHT TRUCK, LICENSE #(NY)PB6024. THE DRIVER'S LAST STOP OF THE DAY WAS AT COMPUTER & SOURCE MICROFILMING ON 145 MIDLER DRIVE - SYRACUSE, NY - EPA #NYD982726747. THE DRIVER INSPECTED THE DRUMS TO INSURE THEY WERE IN GOOD CONDITION PRIOR TO LOADING THEM AS HE DOES AT ALL PICK UP LOCATIONS. THE DRUMS WERE LOADED, MANIFESTS AND OTHER REQUIRED PAPERWOEK WAS COMPLETED, THE TRUCK WAS PLACARDED ACCORDINGLY, AND THE DRIVER DEPARTED FROM COMPUTER & SOURCE MICROFILMING. EVIDENTLY, WHILE ENROUTE BACK TO OUR FACILITY ONE THE DRUMS LOADED AT COMPUTER & SOURCE MICROFILMING DEVELOPED A LEAK IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM. WHEN THE DRIVER, ALLEN SNETSINGER, PULLED OUT OF THE TOLL BOOTH AT EXIT 34 - CANASTOTA, NY, PERSONNEL AT THE BOOTH NOTICED LIQUID DRIPPING OUT OF THE REAR PORTION OF THE VEHICLE. THE THRUWAY AUTHORITY TELEPHONED US IMMEDIATELY TO ALERT US OF THE SPILL. NES IMMEDIATELY PREPARED OUR REMEDIATION CREW FOR DISPATCH TO ASSESS AND CLEAN UP THE SPILL. AT THAT SAME TIME THE NEW TRANSPORT VEHICLE PULLED INTO OUR FACILITY WHERE HE WAS RECEIVED BY THE REMEDIATION CREW QUICKLY PUT A DRUM UNDERNEATH PROPERTIES OF THE LEAKING WASTE TO COLLECT IT. AFTER ASSESSING THE LEAKER WAS LOCATED AND TURNED UPSIDE DOWN TO STOP THE RELEASE. FROM THE LABEL ON THE DRUM IT WAS ASCERTAINED TO BE THE MATERIAL LISTED ON MANIFEST NO. NYB4334967 ENTRY D (COPY ATTACHED). THE WASTE WAS MAINLY WATER WHICH CONTAINED CHROMIUM AND SILVER ABOVE THE REGULAT ORY LIMITS (DOO7 & DO11). THE REMEDIATION CREW DROVE TO THE EXIT 34 TOLL BOOTH TO CLEAN UP WHAT WAS DESCRIBED  AS A "PUDDLE". THE WASTE WAS SOAKED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIALS AND PUT INTO A 55 GALLON OPEN TOP DRUM. THE ROADWAY WAS THEN PRESSURE WASHED, THE FACILITY PERSONNEL WERE SHOVELING UP DIRT WHICH WAS CONTAMINATED NEAR THE FACILITY ENTRANCE/ROAD. BASED UPON THE VOLUME OF WASTE REMAINING IN THE ORIGINAL DRE\UM AND THAT WHICH WAS RECOVERED AT THE TOLL BOOTH, NES ESTIMATES A LOSS OF BETWEEN 10 - 20 GALLONS OF WASTE MATERIAL. RUSS WALTERS OF COMPUTER & SOURCE MICROFILMING WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SPILL EARLY ON DURING OUR RESPONSE EFFORTS. SINCE THE SPILL INVOLVED A HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE WITH AN RQ OF 1 LB., THIS WAS TECHNICALLY AN RQ SPILL.

column42: ORGANOPHOSPHORUS PESTICIDES, LIQUID, TOXIC, FLAMMABLE, FLASH POINT NOT LESS THAN 23 DEGREES C
column168: ON 11/24/92 INERLINE CARRIER HAD HOOKED UP TO CONTAINER ITLU188143. DURING INSPECTION OF CHASSIS IN THE INSPECTION LANE, THE CHASSIS APPEARED WET FROM A LEAKAGE COMING FROM INSIDE THE CONTAINER.  THE DRIVER PULLED THE CONTAINER TO THE INSPECTON DOCK AND NOTIFIED ME.  I IDENTIFIED THE COMMODITY AND CONTACTED THE PORT OF HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT.  I HAD THE AREA SECURED FROM FLOW OF TRAFFIC.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL DRESSED IN PROTECTIVE CLOTHING AIR PACKS AND OPENED THE CONTAINER TO EVALUATE SITUATION.  ONE DRUM WAS FOUND LEAKING.  IT WAS A VERY SLOW LEAK.  I PROVIDED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WITH A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET.  I CONTACTED KIRT PETERSON WITH CHEMINOVA AND ADVISED OF SITUATION.  THEY CONTACTED ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE (EMTECH) TO RESPOND TO CONTAIN THE SPILL, CLEAN UP AND DECONTAMINATION.  NORMAN DRISKELL WITH EMTECH ARRIVED WITH HIS TEAM.  THEY REOPENED CONTAINER, PLACED BISQUINI, PLACED IN A DRUM AND DECONTAMINATED FLOOR WITH BLEACH AND WATER.  NO PRODUCT WAS EVER RELEASED ON GROUND.  THE PORT'S FIRE DEPARTENT CLOTHING WAS PLACED IN A DRUM, SEEALED AND BANDED INSIDE THE CONTAINER.  CONSIGNEE WILL DECONTAMINATE AND DISPOSE OF ACCORDING TO ALL REGULATIONS.  CONTAINER WAS RESEALED.  EMTECH COMPLETED BY 6PM.  GATES WERE REOPENED FOR USUAL TRAFFIC.  I CONTACTED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AROUND 2:50PM AND FILED REPORT.  MISS PORTER ASSIGNED FILE NUMBER 146250.  EMTECH ADVISED THERE WAS A SMALL PINHOLE IN BOTTOM OF DRUM WHICH CAUSED THE LEAK.  IT WAS UNDETERMINED WHAT CAUSED THE PINHOLE. EMTECH PROVIDED THE TWO ATTACHED PICTURES, BUT DID NOT PROVIDE MARKINGS ON DRUM OR SPECS OF DRUM.

AT APPROXIMATELY 5:20PM 11-15-92 ATM C.M. LAGRONE REPORTED BY PHONE TO GENERAL EQUIPMENT FOREMAN L. M. BLOCK THAT SWITCHMAN WIGGINS SAID GATX 93562 HAD FOUL ODOR. AFTER INVESTIGATION L.M. BLOCK FOUND A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCE HAD COME FROM AROUND MANWAY COVER ONTO TANK ACCOUNT OF DEFECTIVE GASKET.  GATX 93562 WAS ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  THE SHIPPER ARRIVED 11-17-92, 10:00AM.  THEY CHANGED MANWAY COVER GASKET AND CAR WAS RELEASED. NOTE: NO PRODUCT GOT ON GROUND.

SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) T.M. ROBINSON WAS NOTIFIED BY MANAGER OF MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE, J. OSBURN, THE FRA INSPECTOR HAD DISCOVERED TWO LEAKING TANK CARS, UTLX 630069 AND UTLX 630089. THE FRA INSPECTOR STATED THAT THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK WAS DUE TO LOOSE BOLTS ON THE MANWAY. CAR WAS SET OUT AND SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED. M. BLANCHARD AND D. DRENNAN OF VININGS ALUMINA PRODUCTS RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT. THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE FOUND TO BE SECURE BUT A SMALL AMOUNT OF DRIED RESIDUE WAS FOUND AROUND THE MANWAY. THE MANWAY GASKETS WERE REPLACED AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE. CARS WERE THEN RELEASED FOR FURTHER TRANSPORTATION.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: AT 0053, RAMP LEAD, GARY BARNES REPORTED AND ODOR OF GASOLINE, TOPSIDE OF THE AIRCRAFT PARKED AT GATE B-61.  UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE, I, TONY FRYE, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR, TOOK THE GAS DETECTION INSTRUMENT AND WENT TO THE TOPSIDE OF THE AIRCRAFT.  THEURE WAS NO ABNORMAL READINGS ON THE GAS DETECTION INSUTRMENT, BUT I COULD DETECT A SLIGHT ODOR OF GASOLINE.  PART-TIME SPILL SPECIALIST, MARK GRIFFITH AND JON MOOTS DONNED FIRE FIGHTING GEAR AND SELF-CONTAINED BREATHING APPARATUS TO OFFLOAD THEUNIT LOAD DEVICES TO SEE IF WE COULD LOCATE THE ONE THAT WAS CAUSING THE GASOLINE ODOR.  THE GASLONE ODOR WAS FOUND TO BE COMING FROM ONE OF THE UNIT LOAD DEVICES THAT WAS MARKED TO CONTAIN HAZ MAT FREIGHT.  INSIDE THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE WAS SIX SHIPMENTS, FOUR OF THEM CONTAINED GASOLINE. EACH WAS IN A FIBERBOARD BOX, CONTAINING ONE GALLON EACH.  EACH FIBERBOARD BOX CONTAINED A ONE GALLON, METAL RECEPTICLE, WITH A SCREW-YPE CLOSURE. THERE WA SNO MEANS TO SECURE THE SCREW-TYPE CLOSURE.  ONE OF THE FOUR PIECES  HAD LEAKED SLIGHTLY TO MOISTEN THE FIBERBOARD BOX THAT IT WAS CONTAINED IN.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND PROPER CERTIFICATION DID ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND FORWARDED ONTO ITS DESTINATION.

AT 0140, JIM CURTIS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AREA MANAGER, REPORTED A UNIT LOAD DEVICE THAT WAS GIVING OFF A STRONG ODOR AND THERE WAS A LIQUID IN THE BOTTOM.  UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE, I TONY FRYE, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR, CHECKED THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE AND DETECTED AN ODOR OF INK. THERE WAS APPROXIMATELY ONE QUART OF THE INK IN THE BOTTOM OF THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE.  RANDY WILLIMAS, PART-TIME SPILL SPECIALIST, DONNED FIRE FIGHTING PROTECTIVE CLOTHING AND AN ORGANIC VAPOR CARTRIDGE RESPIRATOR TO INVESTIGATE THE SHIPMENT.  THIS WAS A FIBERBOARD BOX THAT CONTAINER A ONE GALLON, METL, FRICTION TYPE RECEPTICLE.  THERE WAS A SLIGHT INDENTATION AROUND THE TOP OF THE METAL RECEPTICLE.  THIS IS WHERE THE INK LEAK OCCURED.  THE FIBERBOARD BOX WAS SATURATED WITH THE INK.  I COULD NOT SEET THE SPECIFICATION MARKINGS DUE TO THE SATURATION OF THE LIQUID.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MAKRED, LABELED AND PROPER CERTIFICATION DID ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THAT ITS CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND FORWARDED ONTO ITS DESTINATION.

ON 11/12/92 JACK ELLIOTT ATTEMPTED TO UNLOAD ANHYDROUS INTO A STORAGE TANK AT LINDBURY HEAT TREATING. AFTER JACK MADE HIS CORPORATION HE STARTED HIS LIQUID PUMP.  WITHIN SECONDS JACK NOTICED A LEAR FROM HIS METER.  HE IMMEDIATELY SHUTDOWN THE SYSTEM AND ISOLATED THE LEAK.  THE PROBLEM WAS CORRECTED ON 11/13/92.

column42: FORMALDEHYDE SOLUTION (FLASH POINT MORE THAN 141 DEG F.; IN CONTAINERS OF 110 GALLONS OR LESS)
column168: WHEN TRAILER ARRIVED AT ANDALUSIA, AL.  PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM TRAILER. UPON UNLOADING TRAILER, WE DISCOVERED LEAKAGE AT 2 POINTS ON BULKDRUM. THERE WERE 3 HOLES IN SIDE OF BULK DRUM,  APPEARED TO BE CAUSED BY EITHER BEING STRUCK OR BY METAL FATIGUE.  SECOND AREA OF LEAKAGE APPEARED TO BE WHERE THE VAST MAJORITY OF PRODUCT WAS LOST-THE VALVE AREA AT THE BOTTOM FRONT OF BULKDRUM.  THERE WERE DENTS VISABLE ON THE CONTAINER NEAR THE VALVE OPENING, BUT, THEY APPEARED TO BE OLD.  WE WERE UNABLE TO TELL IF THE VALVE ITSELF WAS DAMAGED, BUT THE VALVE AREA IS WHERE 90% OF THE LEAKAGE OCCURED.  VALVE IS LOCATED IN "INDENTED AREA AND HARD TO VISUALLY INSPECT. REPORTED TO NRC 11/30/92 NRC#146986 ALA DEPT OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT NOTIFIED 11/30/92 CHRIS SMITH PRODUCT IS USED AS A DEODORIZER FOR PORTAJOHNS-PER MANAFACTURER FOMALDEHYDE MAKES UP APPROX 26% OF TOTAL SOLUTION-HOWEVER RQ WAS EXCEEDED.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: THIS SINGLE-TRUCK ACCIDENT HAPPENED AROUND 3:30 P.M. FRIDAY, N OV. 27, 1992 ON VA 205 AT POTOMAC BEACH, ABOUT TWO MILES WEST OF COLONIAL BEACH, WESTMORELAND COUNTY, VA.  A 1990 FORD TANK WAGON, CARRYING 548 GALLONS OF NO. 2 FUEL OIL, OVERTURNED ON THE BRIDGE CROSSING GOLDMAN'S CREEK, RESULTING IN APPARENTLY SLIGHT INJURIES TO THE DRIVER, NEARLY TOTAL DAMAGE TO THE TRUCK, A RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 350 GALLONS OF NO 2 FUEL OIL INTO A TIDAL ESTUARY OF THE POTOMAC RIVER, AND OTHER PROPERTY DAMAGE. THE TRUCK WAS DRIVEN BY JAMES CARLTON HUDSON, 64, OF 812 BANCROFT AVE., COLONIAL BEACH, VA. 22443.  HE WAS RELEASED FROM MARY WASHINGTON HOSPITAL IN FREDERICKSBURG AFTER TREATMENT FOR SCRATCHES AND BRUISES.  HUDSON HAD BEEN DRIVING FUEL TRUCKS FOR 40 YEARS.  MOST OF HIS EXPERIENCE WAS WITH NORMAL OIL COMPANY OF COLONIAL BEACH, WHICH CLOSED IN 1990.  HE BEGAN WORKING FOR PEOPLES OIL CO. IN JANUARY, 1990. HUDSON WAS EAST-BOUND ON VA. 205 WHEN THE ACCIDENT HAPPENED.  THE WEATHER AT THE TIME WAS CLEAR, ALTHOUGH IT HAD BEEN RAINING EARLIER IN THE DAY AND THE PAVEMENT MAY HAVE BEEN DAMP.  ACCORDING TO UNVERIFIED REPORTS HEARD AT THE ACCIDENT SCENE, AN EYEWITNESS BOBBY STEPHAN WAS IN A CR DIRECTLY BEHIND HUDSONS'S TRUCK. REPORTEDLY, HUDSON'S TRUCK WAS TRAVELING ABOUT 38 MILES-PER-HOUR, WHICH IS WITHIN THE 45 MPH SPEED LIMIT FOR THAT SECTION OF HIGHWAY.  HUDSON REMEMBERS WAVING TO THE OCCUPANTS OF AN ON-COMING CAR. HIS RIGHT REAR WHEEL WAN OFF THE PAVEMENT ONTO THE RIGH SHOULDER OF THE ROAD, WHICH WAS SOFT DUE TO RECENT RAINS.  WHEN HE BROUGHT THE TRUCK BACK ONTO THE PAVEMENT, HE WENT INTO A SKID. HIS TRUCK SKIDDED DOWN THE HILL AND OVERTURNED ON THE BRIDGE, COMING TO REST WHICH WITH DRIVER'S SIDE DOWN AND WITH THE CAB OF THE TRUCK FACING BACK TOWARD THE WEST.  THE ACCIDENT DAMAGED THE GUARDRAIL LEADING TO THE BRIDGE AND THE CONCRETE RAIL OF THE BRIDGE ITSELF.  THE SHEARINGMOTION OF THE TRUCK FALLING AGAINST THE BRIDGE RAILING SEVERELY DAMAGED TRUCK'S CAB AND 2500-GALLON ALUMINUM TANK.  HUDSON'S EXIT FROM THE CAB WAS ASSISTED JIMMY WILKERSON AND DAVID BELFIELD, WHO WERE WORKING AT WILKERSON'S SHOP 100 FEET FROM THE BRIDGE.

SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZMAT (SSA/HM) G.B.REEDER WAS NOTIFIED THAT SWITCHING CREW HAD NOTED LIQUID LEAKING OUT OF A PIPE ON THE BOTTOM OF PSPX 596.  MANAGER MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE, BUD WITT, RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  LIQUID WAS COMING FROM A STEAM COIL PIPE ON THE B END OF THE CAR. CAP WAS REPLACED ON THE PIPE WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.  T. DEARING OF PHILLIPS 66 REQUESTED THAT THE CAR BE MOVED BACK TO SWEENY, TX, FOR UNLOADING.  CAR WAS TO BE SENT TO REPAIR FACILITY FOR INSPECTION AND REPAIR, IF NECESSARY. SSA/HM REEDER WAS NOT CERTAIN THAT IT WAS PRODUCT THAT WAS LEAKING. T.DEARING OF PHILLIPS WILL REPORT FINDING OF THE INSPECTION TO SSA/HM REEDER TO DETERMINE ACTUAL CAUSE.  NO FURTHER INFORMATION HAS BEEN REPORTED AS OF THIS DATE.
DRIVER PUT TOO MUCH PRODUCT IN FIRST COMPARTMENT OF TRAILER.  PRODUCT CLEANED UP WITH OIL DRY NATIONAL RESPONSE REPORT #145062

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Derailment
column168: SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM)H.W. RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED THAT CHVX 180078 HAD DERAILED NEAR TINTIC, UTAH.  CAR WAS ON ITS SIDE BUT WAS NOT LEAKING.  SSA/HM RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED A TANK PRESSURE OF 50 PSI AND A MINOR LEAK IN THE GAUGING DEVICE PACKING GLAND.  LOOSE PACKING GLAND NUT WAS SUSPECTED TO HAVE EXISTED BEFORE THE DERAILMENT. PACKING GLAND NUT WAS TIGHTENED WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK. DAMAGE TO THE CAR WAS CONFINED TO COSMETIC DAMAGE TO THE SHELL AND SAFETY APPLIANCES.  CAR WAS UPRIGHTED AND SECURED FOR FURTHER TRANSPORATION.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

THE FREIGHT WAS PICKED UP FROM VAN WATERS ON 11-13 92 AND BROUGHT BACK TO OUR YARD IN DALLAS.  WHEN THE DRIVER DROPPED THE TRAILER HE NOTICED A WET SPOT ON THE BOTTOM OF THE TRAILER.  HE INFORMED THE DOCK THAT THERE MIGHT BE A POSSIBLE PROBEM WITH THE FREIGHT.  THE DOCK FOREMAN THEN ASSIGNED TWO MEMBERS OF OUR RESPONSE TEAM TO HANDLE THE SITUATION. THE RESPONSE PERSONNEL CONTACTED TONY CONWAY FOR INSTRUCTIONS I INFORMED THEM ON WHAT STEPS TO TAKE TO CONATIN THE SPILL AND ALSO TO CONTACT THE SHIPPER. VAN WATERS SENT A REPRESENTATIVE TO THE LOCATIONS TO INVESTIGATE THE SITUATION AND ASSIST IN THE REPONSE. HE MADE THE DETERMINATION THAT THERE WAS A SEAM FAILURE AND MADE THE REPAIR TO THE TANK.  THE RESPONSE TEAM ALONG WITH THE VAN WATERS REP. MADE THE CLEANUP AND FILED A REPORT WITH THE PROPER AUTHORITIES.

(A & B) BERNIE CRAWFORD WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON GENESEE STREET AT AN MPH).  DRIVER WAS IN LANE #1 (CLOSEST TO THE CURB) OF A FOUR LANE NYS TURNED LEFT TO ENTER THE MCDONALD'S RESTAURANT.  TO AVOID COLLIDING WITH CAME TO AN EMERGENCY STOP AT THE RESTAURANT DRIVEWAY.  THE CARGO STRAPS THE VAN WITH CONSIDERABLE FORCE.  DRIVER DISMOUNTED FROM THE TRACTOR, TORN LOOSE.  DRIVER ALSO NOTED THAT PALLETS AND TONS WERE VISIBLE THROUGH THE REAR OF THE TRAILER SO HE WALKED TO THE REAR AND INSPECTED THE WERE FLICKERING AND SHORTING OUT.  RATHER THAT RISK THE POSSIBLILTY OF A PLANT.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE PLANT,  THE TAILGATE COULD NOT BE LOWERED WAS INFORMED THAT THE DAMAGE WOULD BE EVALUATED IN THE DAYLIGHT HOURS. 5:55 PM, SAME DATE, JOE CAVANAUGH, PLANT MANAGER, RECEIVED A CALL FROM THE HAD BEEN FOUND AND THAT THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZMAT HAD RESPONDED AND CLOSED THE STREET TO ALL TRAFFIC.  JOE THEN IMPLEMENTED HIS ERT RECALL NOTIFICATION.  JIM MURRAY, BRANCH MANAGER, ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AT ABOUT 6:35 PM AND APPROACHED THE CONTAINER FROM UPWIND.  ONE CAME TO REST BETWEEN THE CURB AND THE SIDEWALK.  THIS CONTAINER NUMBER TN-2050J WAS PHYSICALLY INSPECTED AND OTHER THAN SCRATCHES SHOWED NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING.  THE OTHER CONTAINER CAME TO REST ON THE LAWN ABOUT 9 PACES FROM THE CURB.  THIS SECOND CONTAINER, NUMBER TN-8457J, WAS ALSO PHYSICALLY INSPECTED AND OTHER THAN SCRATCHES SHOWED NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKAGE.  BOTH TONS HAVE SINCE PASSED A HYDROSTATIC TEST. ASSISTANT FIRE CHIEF WAS BRIEFED ON MY EVALUATION AND I WAS GIVEN PERMISSION TO REMOVE THE CONTAINERS AND TRANSPORT THEM TO THE PLANT.  CONTAINERS WERE PICKED UP WITH THE USE OF A FORKLIFT AND PLACED ON A TRAIGHT TRUCK, THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE PLANT FOR FURTHER DISPOSITION.  THIS HAZMAT REPORT IS SUBMITTED BECAUSE ROUTE WAS CLOSED.
